'''Jean Pitard''' (born ~1228 near [[Bayeux]], France, died in Paris at age 87, in ~1315<ref>{{Cite book|first=Frédéric |last=Pluquet |year=1829 |title=Essai historique sur la ville de Bayeux et son arrondissement |language=fr |publisher=T. Chalopin |location=[[Caen]] |page=423}} [https://books.google.fr/books?id=QzQbAAAAYAAJ at Google Books]</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Henschel |first=August Wilhelm Eduard Theodor |author-link=August Wilhelm Henschel |display-authors=etal |year=1847 |title=Biographisch-litterärische Notizen, berühmte Wundärzte und Aerzte des XIII. und XIV. Jahrhunderts |language=de |magazine=Janus: Central-Magazin für Geschichte u. Litterärgeschichte d. Medicin, ärztl. Biographik, Epidemiographik, medicinische Geographie und Statistik |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=132–151, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cPJLAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA150 page 150] |}}</ref><ref>Others suggest his birth occurred 20 years later, ~1248, and his death in ~1328. {{Cite journal |last=Thomas |first=Antoine |year=1916 |title=Jean Pitart, chirurgien et poète |journal=Comptes rendus des séances de l'Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres |language=fr |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=95&ndash;111 |url=http://www.persee.fr/docAsPDF/crai_0065-0536_1916_num_60_1_73676.pdf |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6phcY9yA6?url=http://www.persee.fr/docAsPDF/crai_0065-0536_1916_num_60_1_73676.pdf |archive-date=13 April 2017 |deadurl=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>) was the royal surgeon to [[Louis IX of France|Louis IX]], [[Philip III of France|Philip the Bold]] and [[Philip IV of France|Philip the Fair]] of France. At his request, about the year 1270, Louis IX created the Fraternity of St. Cosmas and St. Damian,<ref>''Confrérie de Saint-Côme et de Saint-Damien'' {{Cite web|title=Le Médecin et le chirurgien |publisher=[[Paris Descartes University|Université Paris-Descartes]] |language=fr |url=https://www.univ-paris5.fr/content/view/print/3672 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326174145/https://www.univ-paris5.fr/content/view/print/3672 |archive-date=26 March 2017 |deadurl=no}}</ref> which defined and organized the profession of surgeons in France.<ref>{{Cite web|language=French|author=Gourdol, Jean-Yves|title=Portraits de Médecins: Histoire des chirurgiens, des barbiers et des barbiers-chirurgiens (History of Surgeons, Barbers and Barber-surgeons) |publisher=Medarus|url=http://www.medarus.org/Medecins/MedecinsTextes/divers_institutions/chirurgiens_barbiers.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207072007/http://www.medarus.org/Medecins/MedecinsTextes/divers_institutions/chirurgiens_barbiers.html |archive-date=7 February 2009 |deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Gründer, Johann W. Ludwig|year=1859|title=Geschichte der Chirurgie, von den Urzeiten bis zu Anfang des achtzehnten Jahrhunderts|language=German|location=Breslau, Prussia (now Wrocław, Poland)|publisher=Trewendt et Granier|page=[https://books.google.com/books?&id=LehLAAAAcAAJ&pg=PG154 154]|oclc=6318037}}</ref>

Pitard received his training as an apprentice and did not receive any university training, as a result he was not encumbered by many of the medical and anatomical theories of his contemporaries.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Bullough, Vern L.|year=1959|title=Training of the Nonuniversity-Educated Medical Practitioners in the Later Middle Ages|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|volume=14|issue=10 |pages=446–458|doi=10.1093/jhmas/XIV.10.446}}</ref>

