{{about|a documentary film|suburb of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Warrendale, Pennsylvania|the community in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]|Warrendale, Detroit|the community in Oregon|Warrendale, Oregon}}
{{Infobox film | name = Warrendale | image_size = | image = Warrendale FilmPoster.jpeg | caption = | director = [[Allan King]] | producer = | writer = | narrator = | starring = | music = | cinematography = [[William Brayne]] | editing = | distributor = | released = {{Film date|1967}} | runtime = | country = [[Canada]] | language = [[English language|English]] | budget = | gross = }}
'''''Warrendale''''' is a 1967 [[documentary film]] by [[Canadians|Canadian]] filmmaker [[Allan King]]. It was originally produced for broadcast on [[CBC Television]], but was never shown due to King's refusal to edit out the copious profanity in the footage.
The film is a [[cinéma vérité]] look at the lives of emotionally disturbed children housed in a facility named Warrendale, in [[Rexdale]], at the time, a [[Toronto]] suburb. The facility was considered innovative, and met with approval when it first opened in December 1965. But almost a year after it opened, it became the centre of several controversies in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]], and was eventually closed.<ref name=Historicist>{{cite news | last1 = Wencer | first1 = David | title = Historicist: Warrendale, a Mental Health Treatment Centre for Children | url = http://torontoist.com/2013/03/historicist-warrendale-a-mental-health-treatment-centre-for-children/ | accessdate = 12 March 2015 | work = Torontoist | date = 2013-03-30 | ref = harv | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/6WyyTuY1S?url=http://torontoist.com/2013/03/historicist-warrendale-a-mental-health-treatment-centre-for-children/ | archivedate = 2015-03-12 | deadurl = no | location = Toronto | df = }}</ref> Founder John Brown was a New Democratic Party member of the Legislature from 1967 to 1971.
''Warrendale'' won awards at the [[Cannes Film Festival]], and French director [[Jean Renoir]] declared King a great artist.
In 2002, ''Warrendale'' was honoured as a "MasterWork" by the [[Audio-Visual Preservation Trust of Canada]].<ref>[http://avtrust.ca/masterworks/2002/en_film_3.htm]</ref>
